    \section{\mysidestyle Summary of Current Research}
Scalability in computer systems has recently become a problem since general purpose computers (desktop computers) start to use a very large amount of processor cores.
The scalability problem means that the performance of the processor does increase at the same rate as cores are added, but slower.
In the same way, thermal, energy and power scaling also poses problem to these new type of processors.
When packing a large amount of core into a single die of silicon, the difficulty of leading heat away increases. 
Furthermore, power is easily wasted if cores are idling without performing any useful task.
This problem will increase as the amount of cores grow since modern operating system are not really suited for this kind of platforms.

My research aims towards increasing energy scalability in the operating system.
Our goal is to design a new type of operating system more suitable for massively parallel processors as the trend goes towards.
The main focus has been on power management and Quality of Service.
A power manager was created exploiting the idea of cloud computing; \textit{you don't pay for more than what you use}.
In this case no power should dissipated if no work is done.
The power manager was integrated into a web server, and controlled the amount of running cores depending of the workload.
Quality of Service, also a term used in cloud computing, is used for \textit{selling} a bundle of processing power to the user.
The clients using the processing power on operating system level are the applications otherwise fighting for the CPU.
We intend to integrate the possibility for applications to express Quality of Service.
The clients are provided with the necessary amount of processing power, but not more.
This leads to a system with high performance and less unnecessary resource waste.


